I'm using response caching and need to set the cache duration based on the content of the response.  
It would be nice if the caching middleware didn't overwrite the cache control header if it exists, I could then do something like thing

``` cs
[HttpGet, ResponseCache(Duration = 10)] // default cache duration 10 seconds
public object Get()
{
   Response.Headers[HeaderNames.CacheControl] = "public,max-age=60"; // override cache duration
   return new { message = "hello" };
}
```

I'm trying to perform some integration tests using the TestServer in Microsoft.AspNetCore.TestHost. However, for every request I send I am receiving Bad Request. I read that some have difficulties when the controllers are in a different assembly so I simply added the TestServer on a sample API project you get when creating a new API and it still fails. What can I do to resolve this error?

Visual Studio 15.7.5.
dotnet-sdk-2.1.302-win-gs-x64

1. Right click solution -> Add -> New Project -> ASP.NET Core Web Application.
2. Choose API, click OK. 
3. Right click project -> Manage NuGet Packages...
4. Choose "Microsoft.AspNetCore.TestHost", click Install.
5. Add the code below to Program.cs `Main()`.
6. Notice you are receiving Bad Request responses.

```csharp
            var builder = new WebHostBuilder()
                .UseEnvironment("Development")
                .UseStartup<Startup>();
            var testServer = new TestServer(builder);

            var client = testServer.CreateClient();
            var response = client.GetAsync("/api/values").Result;
            var content = response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync().Result;
```

